---
import ToolLayout from '../../layouts/ToolLayout.astro';

const SITE = 'https://healthcalculation.com';
const canonical = `${SITE}/guides/how-much-protein-per-day`;

const schemaArticle = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Article',
  headline: 'How Much Protein Do I Need Per Day?',
  description: 'Evidence-based guide to daily protein requirements for adults based on weight, activity level, and goal. Includes recommendations from ISSN and the Academy of Nutrition and Dietetics.',
  url: canonical,
  datePublished: '2026-06-18',
  dateModified: '2026-06-19',
  author: { '@type': 'Organization', name: 'HealthCalculation.com' },
  publisher: { '@type': 'Organization', name: 'HealthCalculation.com', url: SITE },
};

const schemaFaq = [
  {
    q: 'How much protein do I need per day to build muscle?',
    a: 'To build muscle, the International Society of Sports Nutrition (ISSN) recommends 1.6–2.2 g of protein per kg of body weight per day, combined with progressive resistance training. For a 175 lb (80 kg) person, that is 128–176 g/day. Spreading intake across 3–5 meals maximizes muscle protein synthesis.',
  },
  {
    q: 'How much protein per day to lose weight?',
    a: 'During weight loss, higher protein intake (1.2–1.6 g/kg/day) helps preserve lean muscle mass while in a calorie deficit. For a 165 lb (75 kg) person, that is 90–120 g/day. Higher protein also increases satiety, which naturally reduces overall calorie intake.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Is 100g of protein a day enough?',
    a: 'For a sedentary adult weighing around 125 kg (275 lbs), 100 g/day meets the basic RDA of 0.8 g/kg. For most moderately active adults (70–90 kg), 100 g/day falls in the 1.1–1.4 g/kg range — adequate for maintenance but on the lower end for muscle building. Use our Protein Calculator for a personalized target.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Can I eat too much protein?',
    a: 'In healthy adults with normal kidney function, intakes up to 3.5 g/kg/day have not been shown to cause harm. The main practical risk is that very high protein diets can crowd out fiber, fruits, and vegetables. People with pre-existing kidney disease should follow medically supervised limits.',
  },
];
---

<ToolLayout
  title="How Much Protein Do I Need Per Day? (Science-Backed Guide)"
  description="Find out exactly how much protein you need daily based on your weight, activity level, and goal. Includes tables for weight loss, muscle gain, and athletes."
  canonical={canonical}
  schemaFaq={schemaFaq}
  pageIcon="&#129372;"
  heroTitle="How Much Protein Per Day?"
  schemaArticle={schemaArticle}
>

<article class="guide-article">

  <nav class="breadcrumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
    <a href="/">Home</a><span>›</span>
    <a href="/guides">Guides</a><span>›</span>
    <span>How Much Protein Per Day?</span>
  </nav>

  <h1>How Much Protein Do I Need Per Day?</h1>
<p class="guide-meta">&#128197; Last reviewed: June 2026 &nbsp;&middot;&nbsp; HealthCalculation Editorial Team &nbsp;&middot;&nbsp; Sources: ISSN, Academy of Nutrition and Dietetics, WHO</p>

  <p class="guide-lead">The short answer: <strong>0.8 g per kg of body weight</strong> is the minimum for sedentary adults, but most active people need 1.2–2.2 g/kg depending on their goal. A 165 lb (75 kg) moderately active adult needs roughly <strong>90–135 g of protein per day</strong>.</p>

  <div class="guide-cta-box">
    <p>&#129372; <strong>Get your exact number:</strong> use our <a href="/protein-calculator">Protein Calculator</a> — enter your weight, activity level, and goal for a personalized target in grams per day and per meal.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>The Quick-Reference Table</h2>
  <p>The table below shows recommended daily protein intake by goal, based on the <strong>International Society of Sports Nutrition (ISSN) 2017 Position Stand</strong> and the <strong>Academy of Nutrition and Dietetics</strong> guidelines.</p>

  <div class="guide-table-wrap">
    <table class="guide-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Goal</th>
          <th>g per kg body weight</th>
          <th>g per lb body weight</th>
          <th>Example: 165 lbs (75 kg)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Sedentary adult (RDA minimum)</td>
          <td>0.8 g/kg</td>
          <td>0.36 g/lb</td>
          <td>60 g/day</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="highlight">
          <td>Light activity / maintenance</td>
          <td>1.0–1.2 g/kg</td>
          <td>0.45–0.54 g/lb</td>
          <td>75–90 g/day</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Weight loss (preserving muscle)</td>
          <td>1.2–1.6 g/kg</td>
          <td>0.54–0.73 g/lb</td>
          <td>90–120 g/day</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="highlight">
          <td>Muscle building (resistance training)</td>
          <td>1.6–2.2 g/kg</td>
          <td>0.73–1.0 g/lb</td>
          <td>120–165 g/day</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Endurance / competitive athletes</td>
          <td>1.6–2.4 g/kg</td>
          <td>0.73–1.09 g/lb</td>
          <td>120–180 g/day</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h2>Why the RDA of 0.8 g/kg Is Too Low for Most People</h2>
  <p>The 0.8 g/kg Recommended Dietary Allowance (RDA) was designed to prevent protein deficiency in sedentary adults — not to optimize health, performance, or body composition. Research published since the RDA was established consistently shows that higher intakes produce better outcomes for active people:</p>
  <ul class="guide-list">
    <li><strong>Muscle retention during weight loss:</strong> Studies show intakes of 1.2–1.6 g/kg preserve significantly more lean mass during a calorie deficit than the RDA.</li>
    <li><strong>Muscle synthesis:</strong> Resistance-trained individuals require at least 1.6 g/kg to maximize hypertrophy, according to a 2018 meta-analysis in the British Journal of Sports Medicine (Morton et al.).</li>
    <li><strong>Satiety:</strong> Protein is the most satiating macronutrient. Higher protein diets naturally reduce total calorie intake, supporting weight management.</li>
    <li><strong>Older adults:</strong> Adults over 65 may need 1.0–1.2 g/kg or more to counter age-related muscle loss (sarcopenia), per the PROT-AGE study group.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>How to Distribute Protein Throughout the Day</h2>
  <p>Total daily protein matters most, but distribution also plays a role. Each meal can only stimulate a maximum muscle protein synthesis response of roughly <strong>20–40 g of protein</strong> — beyond that, the excess is oxidized for energy rather than used for muscle repair.</p>
  <p>A practical distribution for someone targeting 150 g/day across 4 meals:</p>
  <div class="formula-box">
    Breakfast: 35–40 g (e.g., 3 eggs + Greek yogurt + protein shake)<br>
    Lunch: 35–40 g (e.g., 200g chicken breast + legumes)<br>
    Dinner: 40–45 g (e.g., 200g salmon + cottage cheese)<br>
    Snack/Post-workout: 30–35 g (e.g., protein shake + milk)
  </div>

  <h2>Best High-Protein Foods (With Amounts)</h2>
  <div class="guide-table-wrap">
    <table class="guide-table">
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Food</th><th>Serving</th><th>Protein</th><th>Calories</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Chicken breast (cooked)</td><td>100 g</td><td>31 g</td><td>165 kcal</td></tr>
        <tr class="highlight"><td>Greek yogurt (non-fat)</td><td>200 g</td><td>20 g</td><td>130 kcal</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Eggs (whole)</td><td>2 large</td><td>12 g</td><td>140 kcal</td></tr>
        <tr class="highlight"><td>Salmon (cooked)</td><td>100 g</td><td>25 g</td><td>208 kcal</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Cottage cheese (low-fat)</td><td>200 g</td><td>25 g</td><td>180 kcal</td></tr>
        <tr class="highlight"><td>Whey protein powder</td><td>1 scoop (30 g)</td><td>24 g</td><td>120 kcal</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Lentils (cooked)</td><td>200 g</td><td>18 g</td><td>230 kcal</td></tr>
        <tr class="highlight"><td>Tofu (firm)</td><td>150 g</td><td>16 g</td><td>120 kcal</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Tuna (canned in water)</td><td>100 g</td><td>25 g</td><td>110 kcal</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h2>Protein for Special Populations</h2>
  <p><strong>Older adults (65+):</strong> The PROT-AGE study group recommends 1.0–1.2 g/kg/day as a minimum to slow sarcopenia, with 1.2–1.5 g/kg for those who are physically active or recovering from illness.</p>
  <p><strong>Pregnant women:</strong> The Institute of Medicine recommends an additional 25 g/day above normal intake during pregnancy, totaling approximately 1.1 g/kg/day.</p>
  <p><strong>Plant-based diets:</strong> Plant proteins are generally less bioavailable than animal proteins. Vegans and vegetarians may benefit from targeting the upper range of their goal bracket (e.g., 2.0–2.2 g/kg for muscle building) and combining complementary protein sources.</p>

  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq-list">
    {schemaFaq.map(({ q, a }) => (
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>{q}</summary>
        <div class="faq-body"><p>{a}</p></div>
